# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: film-speed
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:film-speed/110-film] The film is fully housed in a plastic cartridge, which also registers the image when the film is advanced.
[src:film-speed/110-film] There is a continuous backing paper, and the frame number is visible through a window at the rear of the cartridge.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The film does not need to be rewound and is very simple to load and unload.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The film is usually pre-exposed with frame lines and numbers, a feature intended to make it easier and more efficient for photo finishers to print.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Unlike later competing formats, such as disc and APS film, processed 110 negatives are returned in strips, without the original cartridge.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The 110 cartridge was introduced by Kodak in 1972 with Kodak Pocket Instamatic cameras with Kodachrome-X, Ektachrome-X, Kodacolor II, and Verichrome Pan film.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The new pocket-sized cameras became immediately popular, and soon displaced competing subminiature cameras, such as the Minolta 16 series, from the market.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The 16 mm film width allowed Kodachrome film in 110 size to be processed on the existing processing machines that processed movie films in the Standard 8 mm film and 16 mm film sizes.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Fujifilm stopped manufacturing 110 format film in September 2009.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Lomography re-commenced 110 film production in 2011.
[src:film-speed/110-film] As of 2024, they offer 110 Black and White, Color Negative, and a variety of experimental stocks such as Lomochrome Purple and Metropolis.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Estes Industries has long marketed several model rockets, the most notable being the Astrocam, with a simple 110 camera in the nose; the shutter is triggered when the nose cone separates from the rocket body.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Tyco (in their Spy Tech line of toys) made two toy spy cameras in the early 1990s that utilized 110 film, called the Hidden Camera and Reese's Camera.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The Hidden Camera had a periscope-like attachment that used a mirror for taking pictures around corners or behind objects.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The Hidden Camera's shape and size is similar to that of the Minox B.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The only new 110 film available on the market is currently produced by Austrian analogue photography company Lomography.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Such cameras are capable of making high-quality images on 110 film.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Some of these cameras are quite small and still hold appeal to subminiature-photography enthusiasts.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The small negative size of 110 film makes it difficult to enlarge successfully.
[src:film-speed/110-film] For these reasons, the 110 format is associated with prints that are often rather grainy and unsharp.
[src:film-speed/110-film] This has led to the misconception that the cartridge itself is incapable of holding film flat enough for making high-quality negatives.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The 110 cartridge, as specified by Kodak, has a plastic tab on one end.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Camera designers had the option of using this tab to sense film speed, enabling sophisticated cameras to switch between high- and low-speed film.
[src:film-speed/110-film] A short tab indicated high-speed film, and a long tab indicated low-speed film.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Kodak left it to the film manufacturer to decide which film speeds were high or low.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Only a few cameras took advantage of this feature: Rollei A110, Canon 110 ED 20, Minolta 110 Zoom SLR Mark I/II, Minox 110S, Voigtlander Vitoret 110 EL, Pentax Auto 110 and the Kodak Ektralite 10.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Some manufacturers would vary the low speed ASA setting and then change it in later models.
[src:film-speed/110-film] For example, Minox 110S low speed was 64 ASA (Kodachrome then being made for 110) and high 400 ASA: but Canon 110 ED has 80 ASA only, with the 110 ED 20 having 80 and 400 ASA.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The last 110 film that Kodak produced was ISO 400 speed packed in a cartridge that senses as "low" speed.
[src:film-speed/110-film] As shown in the photograph to the right, these cartridges can be modified by hand so that they signal the proper speed to the camera.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Although the format is commonly associated with print film, Kodak also produced Kodachrome 64 slide film in 110 cartridges until 1982.
[src:film-speed/110-film] In 2012 Lomography re-introduced slide film for 110 with their Peacock 200 ASA model.
[src:film-speed/110-film] However, since not all 110 cameras have a settable ASA dial (low or high, depending on presence of a notch in the cassette), a neutral-density filter has to be used over the lens or the exposure compensation dial has to be used where available.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Otherwise, over-exposure by a factor of x2 will result, leading to over-exposed images.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Along with standard-sized slides that fit into standard projectors, 110 slide film could also be processed into smaller format slides.
[src:film-speed/110-film] The latter requires special *Pocket Carousel* projectors, or the Leica 110 projector.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Kodak's Verichrome Pan was the only 110 black and white film produced until 2012, when Lomography manufactured their "Orca" Black and White film at 100 ISO speed.
[src:film-speed/110-film] This speed is supported by most 110 cameras.
[src:film-speed/110-film] Lomography went on to launch color, redscale, and slide film cartridges which, along with black and white, are the only 110 film types in production as of 2022.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Although 126 was once very popular, as of 2008 it is no longer manufactured, however, most photofinishers can process it using standard day load roll film cassettes.
[src:film-speed/126-film] In 1963, Kodak introduced a new film, encased in a plastic cartridge, for which they re-introduced the "126" designation.
[src:film-speed/126-film] (The number was originally used for the unrelated 126 roll film format from 1906 to 1949).
[src:film-speed/126-film] The term "126" was intended to show that 26 mm square images were recorded, using Kodak's common 1xx film numbering system.
[src:film-speed/126-film] However the image size is actually 28×28 mm, which usually was reduced to approximately 26.5×26.5 mm by masking during printing or mounting.
[src:film-speed/126-film] At the nominal 28 mm square size, the image diagonal is 39.6 mm, which is close to the 43.3 mm diagonal of a 135 film frame (24×36 mm); the crop factor or equivalent focal length multiplier is 1.09 based on the diagonal measurements.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The 126 film cartridge and format were defined in ISO 3029, which has since been withdrawn.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Like the 120 format, there is a continuous backing paper, and the frame number is visible through a small window at the rear of the cartridge.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Cameras for this type of film are equipped with a large rectangular window in the back door, through which is visible not only the frame number, but also a portion of the label showing the film type and speed.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The cartridge has a captive take-up spool, but no supply spool: the film and backing paper are simply coiled tightly and placed in the supply end of the cartridge.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The positioning of the image is fixed by the cartridge.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The film is 35 mm wide, but unlike 135 film, it is unperforated, except for one registration hole per image, similar to the earlier 828 film.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The camera is equipped with a sensing pin which falls into this hole when the film is fully advanced to the next frame, at which point the winding knob or lever is locked, so as to prevent winding past the pre-exposed frame lines.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The top edge of the cartridge above the film gate has a square notch in a specific position that signaled the film speed.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Some of the higher-end cameras used this notch to determine the correct exposure, or to set the light meter, if so equipped.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Although the actual films manufactured in 126 cartridge format had speeds varying between ISO 64/19° and ISO 400/27°, the standard defined 20 different speeds, spanning from ISO 20/14° to ISO 1600/33°.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The film was originally available in 12 and 20 image lengths; at the time regular production stopped it was only available in 24 exposure cartridges.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The exposed film is stored on the take-up spool and does not need to be rewound, making the cameras very simple to load and unload.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Kodak published instructions for assembling a simple pinhole camera using a 126 cartridge with typical household materials.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The format was introduced in 1963 by Kodak under the brand name *Kodapak*, together with the Instamatic camera line.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Around ten million cameras were made by Kodak and other companies.
[src:film-speed/126-film] With a few exceptions, the format was mainly used for fairly simple amateur cameras; some of the few high-end models were manufactured by companies included Kodak, Minolta, Rollei, Yashica and Zeiss Ikon.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The 126 cartridge also was used as the basis for a pinhole camera that could be built using household supplies.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Kodak officially discontinued the format on 31 December 1999.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Unused, outdated 126 films continue to show up at thrift stores, estate sales, and online auctions.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Unless they have been stored frozen, they are probably deteriorated and are suitable only for experimenting.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Ferrania in Italy was the last factory producing 126 film.
[src:film-speed/126-film] They marketed an ISO 200 color print film under their *Solaris* brand.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The last scheduled production run took place in April 2007, but an unscheduled production run in late 2007 surprised industry observers and raised hopes that it had not actually been discontinued.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Ferrania's subsequent bankruptcy meant that there was no longer any large-scale factory source for 126 film.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Some photographers reuse the plastic cartridge from outdated 126 films and reload them with fresh 35mm film.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The process is not difficult, but it is not entirely practical since the process must be carried out in the dark, as the 35mm film must be removed from the cartridge.
[src:film-speed/126-film] In addition, the two films have significantly different perforation schemes.
[src:film-speed/126-film] 126 cameras have a film-advance mechanism that relies on one edge perforation per image, and 35mm camera film has eight perforations per image, on both edges of the film.
[src:film-speed/126-film] The photographer must use the film-advance mechanism several times between images, and one edge of each image will have visible perforations.
[src:film-speed/126-film] An adapter is available for photographers without access to 126 cartridges, but the adapter does not fit all cameras.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Because it is 35 mm wide and is developed in industry-standard C-41 process chemistry, processing of most 126 films is readily available, as long as the photofinisher knows that it is standard, 35 mm-wide, C-41 film.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Printing the photos can present problems, because modern film processing equipment often cannot handle the square format of 126 film.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Some specialist photographic printers can correctly handle it.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Standard flatbed scanners that have a light source for scanning film can be used to scan 126 negatives, perhaps using a mask made with black paper.
[src:film-speed/126-film] Note that older film may require uncommon film processing such as C-22.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The term 135 was introduced by Kodak in 1934 as a designation for 35 mm film specifically for still photography, perforated with Kodak Standard perforations.
[src:film-speed/135-film] It quickly grew in popularity, surpassing 120 film by the late 1960s to become the most popular photographic film size.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Despite competition from formats such as 120, 828, 126, 110, and APS, it remains the most popular film size today.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The size of the 135 film frame with its frame's aspect ratio of 2:3 has been adopted by many high-end digital single-lens reflex and digital mirrorless cameras, commonly referred to as "full frame".
[src:film-speed/135-film] Even though the format is much smaller than historical medium format and large format film, being historically referred to as *miniature format* or *small format*, it is much larger than image sensors in most compact cameras and smartphone cameras.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The engineering standard for this film is controlled by ISO 1007 titled '135-size film and magazine'.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The 135 film size is derived from earlier still cameras using lengths of 35 mm movie film, which had the same size but with different perforations.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The 35 mm film standard for motion picture film was established in Thomas Edison's lab by William Kennedy Laurie Dickson.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Dickson took 70 mm film stock supplied by George Eastman's Eastman Kodak Company.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The 70 mm film was cut lengthwise into two equal width (35 mm) strips, spliced together end to end, and then perforated along both edges.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The original picture size was 18×24 mm (half the full frame size later used in still photography).
[src:film-speed/135-film] There were four perforations on each side of a motion picture frame.
[src:film-speed/135-film] While the Leica camera popularized the format, several 35 mm still cameras used perforated movie film before the Leica was introduced in the 1920s.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The first patent for one was issued to Leo, Audobard, and Baradat in England in 1908.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The first full-scale production camera was the Homéos, a stereo camera produced by Jules Richard in 1913 and sold until 1920.
[src:film-speed/135-film] It took 18x24 mm stereo pairs and used two Tessar lenses.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In 1909, the French Étienne Mollier designed a device for small-format photography, the "Cent-Vues", which used the 35 mm perforated film to take consecutive hundred views in 18×24 mm.
[src:film-speed/135-film] He manufactured it, won the gold medal in the Concours Lépine, and in 1910 sold at a small scale and without much success.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The first big-selling 35 mm still camera was the American Tourist Multiple, which also appeared in 1913, at a cost of $175 (~5,600 US Dollars in 2024) The first camera to take full-frame 24×36 mm exposures seems to be the Simplex, introduced in the U.S. in 1914.
[src:film-speed/135-film] It took either 800 half-frame or 400 full-frame shots on 50 ft (15.2 m) rolls.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The Minigraph, by Levy-Roth of Berlin, another half-frame small camera was sold in Germany in 1915.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The patent for the Debrie Sept camera, a combination 35 mm still and movie camera was issued in 1918; the camera sold from 1922.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The Furet camera made and sold in France in 1923 took full-frame 24x36 mm negatives, and was the first cheap small 35 mm camera of similar appearance to more modern models.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The Leica Camera designed by Oskar Barnack used 35 mm film, and proved that a format as small as 24 mm × 36 mm was suitable for professional photography.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Although Barnack designed his prototype camera around 1913, the first experimental production run of ur-Leicas (Serial No.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Full-scale production of the Leica did not begin until 1925.
[src:film-speed/135-film] While by that time, there were at least a dozen other 35 mm cameras available, the Leica was a success.
[src:film-speed/135-film] It came to be associated with the format, mostly because of this 35 mm popularity, as well as the entire company legacy.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Early Leica cameras are considered highly collectable items.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The original Leica prototype holds the record as being the world's most expensive camera, selling for €2.16 million in 2012.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In the earliest days, the photographer had to load the film into reusable cassettes and, at least for some cameras, cut the film leader.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In 1934, Kodak introduced a *135* daylight-loading single-use cassette.
[src:film-speed/135-film] This cassette was engineered so that it could be used in both Leica and Zeiss Ikon Contax cameras along with the camera for which it was invented, namely the Kodak Retina camera.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The Retina camera and this daylight loading cassette were the invention of Dr.
[src:film-speed/135-film] August Nagel's company in December, 1931, and began marketing the *Kodak Retina* in the summer of 1934.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The first Kodak Retina camera was a Typ 117.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The 35 mm Kodak Retina camera line remained in production until 1969.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Kodak also introduced a line of American made cameras that were simpler and more economical than the Retina.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Argus, too, made a long-lived range of 35 mm cameras; notably the Argus C3.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Kodak launched 135-format Kodachrome colour film in 1936.
[src:film-speed/135-film] AGFA followed with the introduction of *Agfacolor Neu* later in the same year.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The designations *235* and *435* refer to 35 mm film in daylight-loading spools, that could be loaded into Contax or Leica style reusable cassettes, respectively, without need of a darkroom.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The *335* was a daylight loading spool for the 24 × 23 mm stereo format.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Reflex viewfinders, both twin-and single-lens, had been used with earlier cameras using plates and rollfilm.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The first 35 mm single-lens reflex (SLR) was the Kine Exakta, introduced in 1936.
[src:film-speed/135-film] World War II interrupted development of the type.
[src:film-speed/135-film] After the war, Exakta resumed development and the Contax S model with the now familiar pentaprism viewing feature was introduced in 1949.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In the 1950s, the SLR also began to be produced in Japan by such companies as Asahi and Miranda.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Asahi's Pentax introduced the instant-return mirror, important for the popularity of SLRs; until then, the viewfinder on an SLR camera blanked as the mirror sprang out of the optical path just before taking the picture, returning when the film was wound on.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Nikon's F model, introduced in March 1959, was a system camera that greatly improved the quality and utility of 35 mm format cameras, encouraging professionals (especially photojournalists) to switch from larger format cameras to the versatile, rugged, and fast SLR design.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Numerous other film formats waxed and waned in popularity, but by the 1970s, interchangeable-lens SLR cameras and smaller rangefinders, from expensive Leicas to "point-and-shoot" pocket cameras, were all using 35 mm film, and manufacturers had proliferated.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Colour films improved, both for print negatives and reversal slides, while black-and-white films offered smoother grain and faster speeds than previously available.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Since 35 mm was preferred by both amateur and professional photographers, makers of film stock have long offered the widest range of different film speeds and types in the format.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The DX film-speed encoding system was introduced in the 1980s, as were single-use cameras pre-loaded with 35 mm film and using plastic lenses of reasonable enough quality to produce acceptable snapshots.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Automated all-in-one processing and printing machines made 35 mm developing easier and less expensive, so that quality colour prints became available not only from photographic specialty stores, but also from supermarkets, drugstores, and big box retailers, often in less than an hour.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In 1996, a smaller format called Advanced Photo System (APS) was introduced by a consortium of photographic companies in an attempt to supersede 135 film.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Due in part to its small negative size, APS was not taken seriously as a professional format, despite the production of APS SLRs.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In the point-and-shoot markets at which the format was primarily aimed, it enjoyed moderate initial success, but still never rivalled the market penetration of 135.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Within five years of its launch, cheap digital compact cameras started becoming widely available, and APS sales plummeted.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Introductory 35 mm SLRs, compact film point-and-shoot cameras, and single-use cameras continue to be built and sold by a number of makers.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Leica introduced the digital Leica M8 rangefinder in 2007, but continues to make its M series rangefinder film cameras and lenses.
[src:film-speed/135-film] A digital camera back for the Leica R9 SLR camera was discontinued in 2007.
[src:film-speed/135-film] On March 25, 2009, Leica discontinued the R9 SLR and R-series lenses.
[src:film-speed/135-film] By the early 2020s, film photography, particularly 35 mm photography, was experiencing a resurgence in popularity.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In a 2021 PetaPixel survey, 75% of respondents expressed interest in newly manufactured analog cameras.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Kodak reported in 2022 that it was having trouble keeping up with demand for 35 mm film.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In 2024, the Pentax 17 and the Aflie TYCH+ 35 mm cameras were released, both using the half-frame format to conserve film.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Retrospekt and Mattel put out the Malibu Barbie FC-11 35 mm camera.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In September 2024, MiNT Camera took pre-orders for the Rollei 35AF, an update of the Rollei 35.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Kodak offered six 35 mm film cameras for sale as of October 2024, including the Ektar H35N, another half-frame camera.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Individual rolls of 135 film are enclosed in single-spool, light-tight, metal cassettes, also known as film canisters, to allow cameras to be loaded in daylight.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The film is clipped or taped to a spool and exits via a slot lined with flocking.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The end of the film is cut on one side to form a leader.
[src:film-speed/135-film] It has the same dimensions and perforation pitch as 35 mm movie print film (also called "long pitch", KS-1870, whereas 35 mm professional motion picture camera films are always "short pitch", BH-1866).
[src:film-speed/135-film] Most cameras require the film to be rewound before the camera is opened.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Some motorized cameras unwind the film fully upon loading and then expose the images in reverse order, returning the film to the cassette; this protects all exposed frames (except the last one or two), should the camera back be accidentally opened; unexposed film gets spoiled, however.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Disposable cameras use the same technique so that the user does not have to rewind.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Since 1983, most film cassettes have been marked with a DX encoding six-digit barcode pattern, which uses a DX number to identify the manufacturer and film type (and thus processing method), and the number of exposures, for the use of photofinishing laboratories.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Conforming cameras detect at least some of these areas; only three contacts are needed to set a light meter for the four most popular film speeds.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The 135 film has been made in several emulsion types and sensitivities (film speeds) described by ISO standards.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Since the introduction of digital cameras the most usual films have colour emulsions of ISO 100/21° to ISO 800/30°.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Films of lower sensitivity (and better picture quality) and higher sensitivity (for low light) are for more specialist purposes.
[src:film-speed/135-film] There are colour and monochrome films, negative and positive.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Monochrome film is usually panchromatic; orthochromatic has fallen out of use.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Film designed to be sensitive to infrared radiation can be obtained, both monochrome and with false-colour (or pseudocolour) rendition.
[src:film-speed/135-film] More exotic emulsions have been available in 135 than other roll-film sizes.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The term *135 format* usually refers to a 24×36 mm film format, commonly known as 35 mm format.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The 24×36 mm format is common to higher-end digital image sensors, where it is typically referred to as *full-frame* format.
[src:film-speed/135-film] On 135 film, the typical cameras produce a frame where the longer dimension of the 24×36 mm frame runs parallel to the length of the film.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The perforation size and pitch are according to the standard specification KS-1870.
[src:film-speed/135-film] For each frame, the film advances 8 perforations.
[src:film-speed/135-film] This allows for 2 mm gaps between frames.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Camera models typically have different locations for the sprocket which advances the film.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Therefore, each camera model's frame may vary in position relative to the perforations.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The film is approximately 0.14 mm thick.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Other image formats have been applied to 135 film, such as the half-frame format of 18×24 mm which earned some popularity in the 1960s, and the 24×24 mm of the Robot cameras.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The successful range of Olympus Pen F cameras utilized the smaller half-frame size, allowing the design of a very compact SLR camera.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Unusual formats include the 24×32 mm and 24×34 mm on the early Nikon rangefinders, and 24×23 mm for use with some stereo cameras.
[src:film-speed/135-film] In 1967, the Soviet KMZ factory introduced a 24×58 mm panoramic format with its Horizont camera (descendants of which are called, in the Roman alphabet, Horizon).
[src:film-speed/135-film] In 1998, Hasselblad and Fuji introduced a 24×65 mm panoramic format with their XPan/TX-1 camera.
[src:film-speed/135-film] There is also a 21×14 mm format used by Tessina subminiature camera.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The film is available in lengths for varying numbers of exposures.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The standard full-length roll has always been 36 exposures (assuming a standard 24×36 frame size).
[src:film-speed/135-film] Through about 1980, 20 exposure rolls were the only shorter length with widespread availability.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Since then, 20 exposure rolls have been largely discontinued in favour of 24- and 12-exposure rolls.
[src:film-speed/135-film] A camera that uses less than the maximum distance between the spools may be able to make one additional exposure.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Self-loading cameras that load the film after being closed don't spoil the additional length provided for conventional loading and can make that additional length available for two or three additional exposures.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The same length can be available for exposure in any camera if it is loaded without exposing the film to light, e.g. in a dark room or a dark bag.
[src:film-speed/135-film] A 27-exposure disposable camera uses a standard 24-exposure cassette loaded in the dark.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Other, mostly shorter, lengths have been manufactured.
[src:film-speed/135-film] There have been some 6-, 8-, 10-, and 15-exposure rolls given away as samples, sometimes in disposable cameras, or used by insurance adjusters to document damage claims.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Twelve-exposure rolls have been used widely in the daily press.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Photographers who load their own cassettes can use any length of film – with a thinner film base, up to 45 exposures will fit.
[src:film-speed/135-film] The Ilford HP black-and-white film, on a thin polyester base, allowed 72 exposures in a single cassette.
[src:film-speed/135-film] They produced special reels and tanks to allow this to be processed.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Digital sensors are available in various sizes.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Professional DSLR cameras usually use digital image sensors which approximate the dimensions of the 35 mm format, sometimes differing by fractions of a millimetre on one or both dimensions.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Since 2007, Nikon has referred to their 35 mm format by the trade mark FX.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Other makers of 35 mm format digital cameras, including Leica, Sony, and Canon, refer to their 35 mm sensors simply as full frame.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Most consumer DSLR cameras use smaller sensors, with the most popular size being APS-C which measures around 23×15 mm (giving it a crop factor of 1.5–1.6).
[src:film-speed/135-film] Compact cameras have smaller sensors with a crop factor of around 3 to 6.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Most smartphones (as of 2024) have a default aspect ratio of 4:3 (1.33).
[src:film-speed/135-film] Mimicking 35mm film in a smartphone requires cropping to a 3:2 (1.5) aspect ratio.
[src:film-speed/135-film] For an authentic homage, one can apply creative digital filters like the ones commonly used in Instagram that map the colour profile to a characteristic look.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Different brands of 35mm film would achieve the creative colour profile through a chemical process.
[src:film-speed/135-film] For example Fuji Velvia film gave the photo a characteristic of saturated colours under daylight, high contrast, and exceptional sharpness.
[src:film-speed/135-film] A true normal lens for 35 mm format would have a focal length of 43 mm, the diagonal measurement of the format.
[src:film-speed/135-film] However, lenses of 43 mm to 60 mm are commonly considered *normal* lenses for the format, in mass production and popular use.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Common focal lengths of lenses made for the format include 24, 28, 35, 50, 85, 105, and 135 mm.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Most commonly, a 50 mm lens is the one considered *normal*; any lens shorter than this is considered a *wide angle* lens and anything above is considered a *telephoto* lens.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Even then, wide angles shorter than 24 mm is called an *extreme wide angle*.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Lenses above 50 mm but up to about 100 mm are called short telephoto or sometimes, as *portrait telephotos*, from 100 mm to about 200 mm are called *medium* telephotos, and above 300 mm are called *long* telephotos.
[src:film-speed/135-film] With many smaller formats now common (such as APS-C), lenses are often advertised or marked with their "35 mm equivalent" or "full-frame equivalent" focal length as a mnemonic, due to the historic prevalence of the 35 mm format.
[src:film-speed/135-film] This 'equivalent' is computed by multiplying (a) the true focal length of the lens by (b) the ratio of the diagonal measurement of the native format to that of the 35 mm format.
[src:film-speed/135-film] As a result, a lens for an APS-C (18×24 mm) format camera body with a focal length of 40 mm, might be described as "60 mm (35 mm equivalent)".
[src:film-speed/135-film] Although its true focal length remains 40 mm, its angle of view is equivalent to that of a 60 mm lens on a 35 mm format (24×36 mm) camera.
[src:film-speed/135-film] Another example is the lens of the 2/3 inch format Fujifilm X10, which is marked with its true zoom range "7.1–28.4 mm" but has a 35 mm-equivalent zoom range of "28–112 mm".
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] In photography, the **35 mm equivalent focal length** is a measure of the angle of view for a particular combination of a camera lens and film or image sensor size.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The term is popular because in the early years of digital photography, most photographers experienced with interchangeable lenses were most familiar with the 35 mm film format.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] On any 35 mm film camera, a 28 mm lens is a wide-angle lens, and a 200 mm lens is a long-focus lens.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The 35 mm equivalent focal length of a particular lens–sensor combination is the focal length that one would need for a 35 mm film camera to obtain the same angle of view.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Two lens-sensor combinations with the same 35 mm equivalent focal length are expected to have the same angle of view.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Most commonly, the 35 mm equivalent focal length is based on equal *diagonal* angle of view.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This definition is also in the CIPA guideline DCG-001.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Alternatively, it may sometimes be based on *horizontal* angle of view.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] 35 mm equivalent focal lengths are calculated by multiplying the actual focal length of the lens by the crop factor of the sensor.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Quoted 35 mm equivalent focal lengths typically ignore depth of field (DOF), which depends on both focal length and aperture.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] The DOF of smaller sensors is deeper at a given f number, due to the smaller absolute aperture diameters corresponding to shorter focal length lenses.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Equivalent depth of field can be calculated the same way using the crop factor.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For example, a 50mm f/2 lens on a 2× crop factor Micro Four Thirds camera would be equivalent to a 100 mm (= 2×50 mm) f/4 (= f/(2×2)) lens on a full-frame digital SLR in terms of field of view, depth of field, total light gathered, and diffraction effects.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However for the purposes of exposure calculations the aperture does not change for different sensor sizes.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] A standard 35 mm film image is 36 mm wide by 24 mm tall (35 mm refers to the height of the film including the perforations for film transport), and the diagonal is 43.3 mm.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] For historical reasons, sensor size specifications such as 1/2.5" do not match the actual sensor size, but are a bit larger (typically about a factor of 1.5) than the actual sensor diagonal.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] This is because these sensor size specifications refer to the size of a camera tube, while the usable sensor size is about 2/3 of the size of the tube.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Tubes are not used on digital cameras, but the same specifications are used.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] Apart from the width- and diagonal-based 35 mm equivalent focal length definitions, there is a third definition: *EFL* = 50 *f* /*d* mm.
[src:film-speed/35-mm-equivalent-focal-length] However, it is not clear to what extent this definition is used.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] Before standardization to 440 Hz, many countries and organizations followed the French standard since the 1860s of 435 Hz, which had also been the Austrian government's 1885 recommendation.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] Johann Heinrich Scheibler recommended A440 as a standard in 1834 after inventing the "tonometer" to measure pitch, and it was approved by the Society of German Natural Scientists and Physicians at a meeting in Stuttgart the same year.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] The American music industry reached an informal standard of 440 Hz in 1926, and some began using it in instrument manufacturing.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] In 1936, the American Standards Association recommended that the A above middle C be tuned to 440 Hz.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] In 1937 Sir James Swinburne, an electrical engineer and avid amateur musician, delivered a lecture to the Royal Musical Association on "The Ideal Scale," discussing the possibility of tuning a scale to pure ratios and adjusting these ratios to maintain consonance across different keys.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] The following year, Swinburne represented the Musical Association at a preliminary conference to determine the British stance on concert pitch.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] British piano tuners had adopted A439 as the standard in 1899, but Swinburne pointed out that 439 was a prime number, whereas 440 could be more easily factored and electronically synthesized.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] In May of 1939, delegates from France, Germany, The Netherlands, Italy, and England convened at Broadcasting House in London, the headquarters of the BBC, to address the issue of concert pitch.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] Representatives from Switzerland and the United States participated via mail.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] The other European delegates concurred with Swinburne's position and agreed to a standard of A440.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] This standard was taken up by the International Organization for Standardization in 1955 as Recommendation R 16, before being formalised in 1975 as **ISO 16**.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] The A440 standard is not universally adhered to.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] Early-music ensembles continue to use older, lower pitch levels.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] Leonard Bernstein often tuned the New York Philharmonic to A442, leading to complaints from the piano tuners' union, although he claimed both the New York and Boston orchestras had used this higher pitch for years.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] A440 is widely used as concert pitch in the United Kingdom and the United States.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] In continental Europe the frequency of A4 commonly varies between 440 Hz and 444 Hz.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] A440 is often used as a tuning reference in just intonation regardless of the fundamental note or key.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] The US time and frequency station WWV broadcasts a 440 Hz signal at two minutes past every hour, with WWVH broadcasting the same tone at the first minute past every hour.
[src:film-speed/a440-pitch-standard] This was added in 1936 to aid orchestras in tuning their instruments.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Niklaus Wirth based his own ALGOL W on ALGOL 60 before moving to develop Pascal.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Algol-W was intended to be the next generation ALGOL but the ALGOL 68 committee decided on a design that was more complex and advanced rather than a cleaned simplified ALGOL 60.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The official ALGOL versions are named after the year they were first published.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] ALGOL 68 is substantially different from ALGOL 60 and was criticised partially for being so, so that in general "ALGOL" refers to dialects of ALGOL 60.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] ALGOL 60 – with COBOL – were the first languages to seek standardization.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] ALGOL 60 was used mostly by research computer scientists in the United States and in Europe.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Its use in commercial applications was hindered by the absence of standard input/output facilities in its description and the lack of interest in the language by large computer vendors.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] ALGOL 60 did however become the standard for the publication of algorithms and had a profound effect on future language development.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] John Backus developed the Backus normal form method of describing programming languages specifically for ALGOL 58.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] It was revised and expanded by Peter Naur for ALGOL 60, and at Donald Knuth's suggestion renamed Backus–Naur form.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Peter Naur: "As editor of the ALGOL Bulletin I was drawn into the international discussions of the language and was selected to be member of the European language design group in November 1959.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Alan Perlis gave a vivid description of the meeting: "The meetings were exhausting, interminable, and exhilarating.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] One became aggravated when one's good ideas were discarded along with the bad ones of others.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Nevertheless, diligence persisted during the entire period.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The language originally did not include recursion.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] It was inserted into the specification at the last minute, against the wishes of some of the committee.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Several authors of the original report met in April 1962 to resolve issues that had arisen.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Their work resulted in the publication of the "Revised report on the algorithmic language ALGOL 60".
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Further clarifications and the inclusion of I/O procedures were made by the Working Group 2.1 of IFIP Technical Committee 2.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] These efforts were published as the "Modified Report on the algorithmic language ALGOL 60" in 1975.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] ALGOL 60 inspired many languages that followed it.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] To date there have been at least 70 augmentations, extensions, derivations and sublanguages of ALGOL 60.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The Burroughs dialects included special system programming dialects such as ESPOL and NEWP.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] ALGOL 60 as officially defined had no I/O facilities; implementations defined their own in ways that were rarely compatible with each other.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] In contrast, ALGOL 68 offered an extensive library of *transput* (ALGOL 68 parlance for input/output) facilities.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] ALGOL 60 provided two evaluation strategies for parameter passing: the common call-by-value, and call-by-name.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The procedure declaration specified, for each formal parameter, which was to be used: *value* specified for call-by-value, and omitted for call-by-name.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Call-by-name recomputes every parameter when it is used in an expression, so has certain effects in contrast to call-by-reference.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] For example, without specifying the parameters as *value* or *reference*, it is impossible to develop a procedure that will swap the values of two parameters if the actual parameters that are passed in are an integer variable and an array that is indexed by that same integer variable.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Think of passing a pointer to swap(i, A[i]) in to a function.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Now that every time swap is referenced, it's reevaluated.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Say i := 1 and A[i] := 2, so every time swap is referenced it'll return the other combination of the values ([1,2], [2,1], [1,2] and so on).
[src:film-speed/algol-60] A similar situation occurs with a random function passed as actual argument.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Call-by-name is known by many compiler designers for the interesting "thunks" that are used to implement it.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Donald Knuth devised the "man or boy test" to separate compilers that correctly implemented "recursion and non-local references." This test contains an example of call-by-name.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The ALGOL 60 reports recognize three different levels of language, i.e., a Reference Language, a Publication Language, and several Hardware Representations.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The Reference and Publication languages have no reserved words, however the reports do recommend reserving some identifiers for standard functions.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The Reference Language has lower case letters and other characters not available in the 6-bit character sets typical of ALGOL 60's era.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The reports briefly describe hardware representations.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Implementations differ in their hardware representations of underlined independent basic symbols.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] They also differ in their hardware representation of delimiters.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] There are 24 basic symbols in the Modified Report that are words in boldface.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Although those words are not reserved in the reference and publication languages, some hardware implementations may reserve them.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] and also the names of all the intrinsic functions.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Implementations differ in how the text in bold must be written.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] For example, the word 'INTEGER', including the quotation marks, must be used in some implementations in place of **integer**, above, thereby designating it as a special ALGOL symbol.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The following version uses the hardware representation supported by the ALCOR compiler for the IBM 7090.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Additionally, it uses `..` to represent the colon character, `.=` for assignment, `(/ and )/` instead of brackets, and `.,` for semicolon.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Since ALGOL 60 had no I/O facilities, there is no portable hello world program in ALGOL.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The following program could (and still will) compile and run on an ALGOL implementation for a Unisys A-Series mainframe, and is a straightforward simplification of code taken from The Language Guide at the University of Michigan-Dearborn Computer and Information Science Department Hello world!
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Where * etc. represented a format specification as used in FORTRAN, e.g.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] An alternative example, using Elliott Algol I/O is as follows.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Elliott Algol used different characters for "open-string-quote" and "close-string-quote", represented here by ‘ and ’ .
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Here's a version for the Elliott 803 Algol (A104) The standard Elliott 803 used 5-hole paper tape and thus only had upper case.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The code lacked any quote characters so £ (pound sign) was used for open quote and ?
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Special sequences were placed in double quotes (e.g£., L?? produced a new line on the teleprinter).
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The ICT 1900 series Algol I/O version allowed input from paper tape or punched card.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] Paper tape 'full' mode allowed lower case.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] LEAP is an extension to the ALGOL 60 programming language which provides an associative memory of triples.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] The three items in a triple denote the association that an Attribute of an Object has a specific Value.
[src:film-speed/algol-60] LEAP was created by Jerome Feldman (University of California Berkeley) and Paul Rovner (MIT Lincoln Lab) in 1967.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The term *speed* comes from the early days of photography.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Photographic emulsions that were more sensitive to light needed less time to generate an acceptable image and thus a complete exposure could be finished faster, with the subjects having to hold still for a shorter length of time.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Emulsions that were less sensitive were deemed "slower" as the time to complete an exposure was much longer and often usable only for still life photography.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Exposure times for photographic emulsions shortened from hours to fractions of a second by the late 19th century.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In both film and digital photography, choice of speed will almost always affect image quality.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Higher sensitivities, which require shorter exposures, typically result in reduced image quality due to coarser film grain or increased digital image noise.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Lower sensitivities, which require longer exposures, will retain more viable image data due to finer grain or less noise, and therefore more detail.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Ultimately, sensitivity is limited by the quantum efficiency of the film or sensor.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] To determine the exposure time needed for a given film, a light meter is typically used.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Five criteria for the rating of emulsion speed have been used since the late 19th century, listed here by name and date, these criteria are: threshold (1880), inertia (1890), fixed density (1934), minimum useful gradient (1939) and fractional gradient (1939).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The threshold criterion is the point on the characteristic curve corresponding to just perceptible density above fog.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The inertia speed point of an emulsion is determined on the Hurter and Driffield characteristic curve by the intercept between the gradient of the straight line part of the curve and the line representing the base + fog (B+F) on the density axis.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The fixed density speed point is determined by defining a fixed minimum density as the basis of the emulsion speed (e.g.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The minimum useful gradient criterion places the speed point where the gradient first reaches an agreed value (e.g. tan 𝜃 = 0.2).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The fractional gradient is defined as the speed point at which the slope of the characteristic curve first reaches a fixed fraction (e.g.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] 0.3) of the average gradient over a range (e.g.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The speed of the emulsion was then expressed in 'degrees' Warnerke (sometimes seen as Warn. or °W.) corresponding with the last number visible on the exposed plate after development and fixation.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Each number represented an increase of 1/3 in speed, typical plate speeds were between 10° and 25° Warnerke at the time.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] His system saw some success but proved to be unreliable due to its spectral sensitivity to light, the fading intensity of the light emitted by the phosphorescent tablet after its excitation as well as high built-tolerances.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The concept, however, was later built upon in 1900 by Henry Chapman Jones (1855–1932) in the development of his plate tester and modified speed system.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Another early practical system for measuring the sensitivity of an emulsion was that of Hurter and Driffield (H&D), originally described in 1890, by the Swiss-born Ferdinand Hurter (1844–1898) and British Vero Charles Driffield (1848–1915).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In their system, speed numbers were inversely proportional to the exposure required.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] For example, an emulsion rated at 250 H&D would require ten times the exposure of an emulsion rated at 2500 H&D.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The methods to determine the sensitivity were later modified in 1925 (in regard to the light source used) and in 1928 (regarding light source, developer and proportional factor)—this later variant was sometimes called "H&D 10".
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The H&D system was officially accepted as a standard in the former Soviet Union from 1928 until September 1951, when it was superseded by GOST 2817–50.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The *Scheinergrade* (Sch.) system was devised by the German astronomer Julius Scheiner (1858–1913) in 1894 originally as a method of comparing the speeds of plates used for astronomical photography.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Scheiner's system rated the speed of a plate by the least exposure to produce a visible darkening upon development.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Speed was expressed in degrees Scheiner, originally ranging from 1° to 20° Sch., with each increment of a degree corresponding to a *multiplicative* factor of increased light sensitivity.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] This multiplicative factor was determined by the constraint that an increment of 19° Sch.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] (from 1° to 20° Sch.) corresponded to a hundredfold increase in sensitivity.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Thus emulsions that differed by 1° Sch. on the Scheiner scale were ${\sqrt[{19}]{100}}=1.2742...$ -fold more (or, less) sensitive to each other.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Scheiner's system was eventually abandoned in Germany, when the standardized DIN system was introduced in 1934.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In various forms, it continued to be in widespread use in other countries for some time.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The DIN system, officially DIN standard 4512 by the **Deutsches Institut für Normung** (then known as the **Deutscher Normenausschuß** (DNA)), was published in January 1934.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] International Congress of Photography (German: **Internationaler Kongreß für wissenschaftliche und angewandte Photographie**) held in Dresden from 3 to 8 August 1931.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The DIN system was inspired by Scheiner's system, but the sensitivities were represented as the base 10 logarithm of the sensitivity multiplied by 10, similar to decibels.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] As in the Scheiner system, speeds were expressed in 'degrees'.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Originally the sensitivity was written as a fraction with 'tenths' (for example "18/10° DIN"), where the resultant value 1.8 represented the relative base 10 logarithm of the speed.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] 'Tenths' were later abandoned with DIN 4512:1957-11, and the example above would be written as "18° DIN".
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The degree symbol was finally dropped with DIN 4512:1961-10.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Originally only meant for black-and-white negative film, the system was later extended and regrouped into nine parts, including DIN 4512-1:1971-04 for black-and-white negative film, DIN 4512-4:1977-06 for color reversal film and DIN 4512-5:1977-10 for color negative film.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] On an international level the German DIN 4512 system has been effectively superseded in the 1980s by ISO 6:1974, ISO 2240:1982, and ISO 5800:1979 where the same sensitivity is written in linear and logarithmic form as "ISO 100/21°" (now again with degree symbol).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] These ISO standards were subsequently adopted by DIN as well.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] When BS 935:1941 was published during World War II, specifying exposure tables for negative materials, it employed the same fixed-density speed criterion used in the German DIN 4512:1934 system.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The British Standard also used *logarithmic* speed numbers, following the example of Scheiner and DIN.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] When the American ASA Z38.2.1:1943 standard was published, it used a fractional gradient speed criterion and *arithmetic* speed numbers, for compatibility with Weston and GE.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] British standard BS 1380:1947 adopted the *fractional gradient* criterion of the American 1943 standard, and also included *arithmetic* speed numbers in addition to *logarithmic* numbers.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The *logarithmic* speed number proposed in the later BS 1380:1957 standard was almost identical to the DIN 4512:1957 standard, except that the BS number was +9 degrees greater than the corresponding DIN number; in 1971, the BS and DIN standards changed this to +10 degrees.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Following an increasing effort to produce international standards, the British, American, and German standards became identical in ISO 6:1974, which corresponded to BS 1380:Part1:1973.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The meter and film rating system were invented by William Nelson Goodwin, Jr., who worked for them and later received a Howard N.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Potts Medal for his contributions to engineering.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The company tested and frequently published speed ratings for most films of the time.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Weston film speed ratings could since be found on most Weston exposure meters and were sometimes referred to by film manufacturers and third parties in their exposure guidelines.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Since manufacturers were sometimes creative about film speeds, the company went as far as to warn users about unauthorized uses of their film ratings in their "Weston film ratings" booklets.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The Weston Cadet (model 852 introduced in 1949), Direct Reading (model 853 introduced in 1954) and Master III (models 737 and S141.3 introduced in 1956) were the first in their line of exposure meters to switch and utilize the meanwhile established ASA scale instead.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Other models used the original Weston scale up until ca.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Vice versa, "old" Weston film speed ratings could be converted into "new" Westons and the ASA scale by adding the same amount, that is, a film rating of 100 Weston (up to 1955) corresponded with 125 ASA (as per ASA PH2.5-1954 and before).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] This conversion was not necessary on Weston meters manufactured and Weston film ratings published since 1956 due to their inherent use of the ASA system; however, the changes of the ASA PH2.5-1960 revision may be taken into account when comparing with newer ASA or ISO values.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Prior to the establishment of the ASA scale and similar to Weston film speed ratings another manufacturer of photo-electric exposure meters, General Electric, developed its own rating system of so-called *General Electric film values* (often abbreviated as *G-E* or *GE*) around 1937.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Film speed values for use with their meters were published in regularly updated *General Electric Film Values* leaflets and in the *General Electric Photo Data Book*.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] General Electric switched to use the ASA scale in 1946.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Meters manufactured since February 1946 are equipped with the ASA scale (labeled "Exposure Index") already.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] For some of the older meters with scales in "Film Speed" or "Film Value" (e.g. models DW-48, DW-49 as well as early DW-58 and GW-68 variants), replaceable hoods with ASA scales were available from the manufacturer.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The company continued to publish recommended film values after that date, however, they were then aligned to the ASA scale.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Originally, ASA values were frequently referred to as *American standard speed numbers* or *ASA exposure-index numbers*.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The ASA scale is a linear scale, that is, a film denoted as having a film speed of 200 ASA is twice as fast as a film with 100 ASA.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The ASA standard underwent a major revision in 1960 with ASA PH2.5-1960, when the method to determine film speed was refined and previously applied safety factors against under-exposure were abandoned, effectively doubling the nominal speed of many black-and-white negative films.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] For example, an Ilford HP3 that had been rated at 200 ASA before 1960 was labeled 400 ASA afterwards without any change to the emulsion.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Similar changes were applied to the DIN system with DIN 4512:1961-10 and the BS system with BS 1380:1963 in the following years.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In addition to the established arithmetic speed scale, ASA PH2.5-1960 also introduced logarithmic ASA grades (100 ASA = 5° ASA), where a difference of 1° ASA represented a full exposure stop and therefore the doubling of a film speed.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] For some while, ASA grades were also printed on film boxes, and they saw life in the form of the APEX speed value *Sv* (without degree symbol) as well.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ASA PH2.5-1960 was revised as ANSI PH2.5-1979, without the logarithmic speeds, and later replaced by NAPM IT2.5–1986 of the National Association of Photographic Manufacturers, which represented the US adoption of the international standard ISO 6.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The latest issue of ANSI/NAPM IT2.5 was published in 1993.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The standard for color negative film was introduced as ASA PH2.27-1965 and saw a string of revisions in 1971, 1976, 1979, and 1981, before it finally became ANSI IT2.27–1988 prior to its withdrawal.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Color reversal film speeds were defined in ANSI PH2.21-1983, which was revised in 1989 before it became ANSI/NAPM IT2.21 in 1994, the US adoption of the ISO 2240 standard.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] On an international level, the ASA system was superseded by the ISO film speed system between 1982 and 1987, however, the arithmetic ASA speed scale continued to live on as the linear speed value of the ISO system.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] GOST (Cyrillic: ГОСТ) was an arithmetic film speed scale defined in GOST 2817-45 and GOST 2817–50.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] It was used in the former Soviet Union from October 1951, replacing Hurter & Driffield (H&D, Cyrillic: ХиД) numbers, which had been used since 1928.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] GOST 2817-50 was similar to the ASA standard, having been based on a speed point at a density 0.2 above base plus fog, as opposed to the ASA's 0.1.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] GOST markings are only found on pre-1987 photographic equipment (film, cameras, lightmeters, etc.) of Soviet Union manufacture.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] This evolved into multiple parts including GOST 10691.6–88 and GOST 10691.5–88, which both became functional on 1 January 1991.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The ASA and DIN film speed standards have been combined into the ISO standards since 1974.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The current International Standard for measuring the speed of color negative film is ISO 5800:2001 (first published in 1979, revised in November 1987) from the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Related standards ISO 6:1993 (first published in 1974) and ISO 2240:2003 (first published in July 1982, revised in September 1994 and corrected in October 2003) define scales for speeds of black-and-white negative film and color reversal film, respectively.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The determination of ISO speeds with digital still-cameras is described in ISO 12232:2019 (first published in August 1998, revised in April 2006, corrected in October 2006 and again revised in February 2019).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The ISO system defines both an arithmetic and a logarithmic scale.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The arithmetic ISO scale corresponds to the arithmetic ASA system, where a doubling of film sensitivity is represented by a doubling of the numerical film speed value.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In the logarithmic ISO scale, which corresponds to the DIN scale, adding 3° to the numerical value constitutes a doubling of sensitivity.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] For example, a film rated ISO 200/24° is twice as sensitive as one rated ISO 100/21°.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Commonly, the logarithmic speed is omitted; for example, "ISO 100" denotes "ISO 100/21°", while logarithmic ISO speeds are written as "ISO 21°" as per the standard.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] and rounding to the nearest integer; the log is base 10.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] and rounding to the nearest standard arithmetic speed in Table 1 below.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] APEX *Sv* values 1 to 10 correspond with logarithmic ASA grades 1° to 10° found in ASA PH2.5-1960.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ASA arithmetic speeds from 4 to 5 are taken from ANSI PH2.21-1979 (Table 1, p.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ASA arithmetic speeds from 6 to 3200 are taken from ANSI PH2.5-1979 (Table 1, p.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ISO arithmetic speeds from 4 to 3200 are taken from ISO 5800:1987 (Table "ISO speed scales", p.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ISO arithmetic speeds from 6 to 10000 are taken from ISO 12232:1998 (Table 1, p.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ISO 12232:1998 does not specify speeds greater than 10000.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] However, the upper limit for *S*noise 10000 was given as 12500, suggesting that ISO may have envisioned a progression of 12500, 25000, 50000, and 100000, similar to that from 1250 to 10000.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] This was consistent with ASA PH2.12-1961.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] For digital cameras, Nikon, Canon, Sony, Pentax, and Fujifilm chose to express the greater speeds in an exact power-of-2 progression from the highest previously realized speed (6400) rather than rounding to an extension of the existing progression.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Speed ratings greater than 10000 have finally been defined in ISO 12232:2019.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Most of the modern 35 mm film SLRs support an automatic film speed range from ISO 25/15° to 5000/38° with DX-coded films, or ISO 6/9° to 6400/39° manually (without utilizing exposure compensation).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The film speed range with support for TTL flash is smaller, typically ISO 12/12° to 3200/36° or less.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The Booster accessory for the Canon Pellix QL (1965) and Canon FT QL (1966) supported film speeds from 25 to 12800 ASA.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The film speed dial of the Canon A-1 (1978) supported a speed range from 6 to 12800 ASA (but already called ISO film speeds in the manual).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] On this camera exposure compensation and extreme film speeds were mutually exclusive.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The Leica R8 (1996) and R9 (2002) officially supported film speeds of 8000/40°, 10000/41° and 12800/42° (in the case of the R8) or 12500/42° (in the case of the R9), and utilizing its ±3 EV exposure compensation the range could be extended from ISO 0.8/0° to ISO 100000/51° in half exposure steps.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] As discussed in the ASA and DIN sections, the definition of the ASA and DIN scales changed several times in the 1950s up into the early 1960s making it necessary to convert between the different scales.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Since the ISO system combines the newer ASA and DIN definitions, this conversion is also necessary when comparing older ASA and DIN scales with the ISO scale.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The picture shows an ASA/DIN conversion in a 1952 photography book in which 21/10° DIN was converted to ASA 80 instead of ASA 100.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Some classic camera's exposure guides show the old conversion as they were valid at the time of production, for example the exposure guide of the classic camera Tessina (since 1957), where 21/10° DIN is related to ASA 80, 18° DIN to ASA 40, etc.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Users of classic cameras may become confused if they are not aware of the historic background of changing standards.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Film speed is found from a plot of optical density vs. log of exposure for the film, known as the *D*–log *H* curve or Hurter–Driffield curve.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] There typically are five regions in the curve: the base + fog, the toe, the linear region, the shoulder, and the overexposed region.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The exposure *H*m, in lux-s, is that for point m when the specified contrast condition is satisfied.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] This value is then rounded to the nearest standard speed in Table 1 of ISO 6:1993.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Determining speed for color negative film is similar in concept but more complex because it involves separate curves for blue, green, and red.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The film is processed according to the film manufacturer's recommendations rather than to a specified contrast.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ISO speed for color reversal film is determined from the middle rather than the threshold of the curve; it again involves separate curves for blue, green, and red, and the film is processed according to the film manufacturer's recommendations.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Film speed is used in the exposure equations to find the appropriate exposure parameters.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Four variables are available to the photographer to obtain the desired effect: lighting, film speed, f-number (aperture size), and shutter speed (exposure time).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The equation may be expressed as ratios, or, by taking the logarithm (base 2) of both sides, by addition, using the APEX system, in which every increment of 1 is a doubling of exposure; this increment is commonly known as a "stop".
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The effective f-number is proportional to the ratio between the lens focal length and aperture diameter, the diameter itself being proportional to the square root of the aperture area.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Thus, a lens set to f/1.4 allows twice as much light to strike the focal plane as a lens set to f/2.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Therefore, each f-number factor of the square root of two (approximately 1.4) is also a stop, so lenses are typically marked in that progression: f/1.4, 2, 2.8, 4, 5.6, 8, 11, 16, 22, 32, etc..
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The ISO arithmetic speed has a useful property for photographers without the equipment for taking a metered light reading.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Correct exposure will usually be achieved for a frontlighted scene in bright sun if the aperture of the lens is set to f/16 and the shutter speed is the reciprocal of the ISO film speed (e.g.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Exposure index, or EI, refers to speed rating assigned to a particular film and shooting situation in variance to the film's actual speed.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] It is used to compensate for equipment calibration inaccuracies or process variables, or to achieve certain effects.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The exposure index may simply be called the *speed setting*, as compared to the speed *rating*.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] For example, a photographer may rate an ISO 400 film at EI 800 and then use push processing to obtain printable negatives in low-light conditions.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Another example occurs where a camera's shutter is miscalibrated and consistently overexposes or underexposes the film; similarly, a light meter may be inaccurate.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] One may adjust the EI setting accordingly in order to compensate for these defects and consistently produce correctly exposed negatives.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Upon exposure, the amount of light energy that reaches the film determines the effect upon the emulsion.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] If the brightness of the light is multiplied by a factor and the exposure of the film decreased by the same factor by varying the camera's shutter speed and aperture, so that the energy received is the same, the film will be developed to the same density.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The systems for determining the sensitivity for an emulsion are possible because reciprocity holds over a wide range of customary conditions.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In practice, reciprocity works reasonably well for normal photographic films for the range of exposures between 1/1000 second to 1/2 second.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] However, this relationship breaks down outside these limits, a phenomenon known as reciprocity failure.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The size of silver halide grains in the emulsion affects film sensitivity, which is related to granularity because larger grains give film greater sensitivity to light.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Fine-grain film, such as film designed for portraiture or copying original camera negatives, is relatively insensitive, or "slow", because it requires brighter light or a longer exposure than a "fast" film.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Fast films, used for photographing in low light or capturing high-speed motion, produce comparatively grainy images.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Kodak has defined a "Print Grain Index" (PGI) to characterize film grain (color negative films only), based on perceptual just-noticeable difference of graininess in prints.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] They also define "granularity", a measurement of grain using an RMS measurement of density fluctuations in uniformly exposed film, measured with a microdensitometer with 48 micrometre aperture.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Granularity varies with exposure — underexposed film looks grainier than overexposed film.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Some high-speed black-and-white films, such as Ilford Delta 3200 and P3200 T-Max are marketed with film speeds in excess of their true ISO speed as determined using the ISO testing method.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] According to the respective data sheets, the Ilford product is actually an ISO 1000 film, while the Kodak film's speed is nominally 800 to 1000 ISO.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The manufacturers do not indicate that the 3200 number is an ISO rating on their packaging.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Kodak and Fuji also marketed E6 films designed for pushing (hence the "P" prefix), such as Ektachrome P800/1600 and Fujichrome P1600, both with a base speed of ISO 400.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The DX codes on the film cartridges indicate the marketed film speed (i.e.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] 3200), not the ISO speed, in order to automate shooting and development.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In digital camera systems, an arbitrary relationship between exposure and sensor data values can be achieved by setting the signal gain of the sensor.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The relationship between the sensor data values and the lightness of the finished image is also arbitrary, depending on the parameters chosen for the interpretation of the sensor data into an image color space such as sRGB.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The usual design is that the camera's parameters for interpreting the sensor data values into sRGB values are fixed, and a number of different EI choices are accommodated by varying the sensor's signal gain in the analog realm, prior to conversion to digital.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Some camera designs provide at least some EI choices by adjusting the sensor's signal gain in the digital realm ("expanded ISO").
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Digital cameras have far surpassed film in terms of sensitivity to light, with ISO equivalent speeds of up to 4,560,000, a number that is unfathomable in the realm of conventional film photography.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The ISO standard ISO 12232:2006 gave digital still camera manufacturers a choice of five different techniques for determining the exposure index rating at each sensitivity setting provided by a particular camera model.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Three of the techniques in ISO 12232:2006 were carried over from the 1998 version of the standard, while two new techniques allowing for measurement of JPEG output files were introduced from CIPA DC-004.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Depending on the technique selected, the exposure index rating could depend on the sensor sensitivity, the sensor noise, and the appearance of the resulting image.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The standard specified the measurement of light sensitivity of the entire digital camera system and not of individual components such as digital sensors, although Kodak has reported using a variation to characterize the sensitivity of two of their sensors in 2001.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The *Recommended Exposure Index* (REI) technique, new in the 2006 version of the standard, allows the manufacturer to specify a camera model's EI choices arbitrarily.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The choices are based solely on the manufacturer's opinion of what EI values produce well-exposed sRGB images at the various sensor sensitivity settings.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] This is the only technique available under the standard for output formats that are not in the sRGB color space.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] This is also the only technique available under the standard when multi-zone metering (also called *pattern* metering) is used.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Because the output level is measured in the sRGB output from the camera, it is only applicable to sRGB images—typically JPEG—and not to output files in raw image format.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] It is not applicable when multi-zone metering is used.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The CIPA DC-004 standard requires that Japanese manufacturers of digital still cameras use either the REI or SOS techniques, and DC-008 updates the Exif specification to differentiate between these values.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Consequently, the three EI techniques carried over from ISO 12232:1998 are not widely used in recent camera models (approximately 2007 and later).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] As those earlier techniques did not allow for measurement from images produced with lossy compression, they cannot be used at all on cameras that produce images only in JPEG format.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The *saturation-based* (SAT or Ssat) technique is closely related to the SOS technique, with the sRGB output level being measured at 100% white rather than 18% gray.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The SOS value is effectively 0.704 times the saturation-based value.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Because the output level is measured in the sRGB output from the camera, it is only applicable to sRGB images—typically TIFF—and not to output files in raw image format.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The two *noise-based* techniques have rarely been used for consumer digital still cameras.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] These techniques specify the highest EI that can be used while still providing either an "excellent" picture or a "usable" picture depending on the technique chosen.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] An update to this standard has been published as ISO 12232:2019, defining a wider range of ISO speeds.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] ISO speed ratings of a digital camera are based on the properties of the sensor and the image processing done in the camera, and are expressed in terms of the luminous exposure *H* (in lux seconds) arriving at the sensor.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] is a factor depending on the transmittance *T* of the lens, the vignetting factor *v*(*θ*), and the angle *θ* relative to the axis of the lens.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] where $H_{\mathrm {sat} }$ is the maximum possible exposure that does not lead to a clipped or bloomed camera output.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Typically, the lower limit of the saturation speed is determined by the sensor itself, but with the gain of the amplifier between the sensor and the analog-to-digital converter, the saturation speed can be increased.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The factor 78 is chosen such that exposure settings based on a standard light meter and an 18-percent reflective surface will result in an image with a grey level of 18%/√2 = 12.7% of saturation.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The factor √2 indicates that there is half a stop of headroom to deal with specular reflections that would appear brighter than a 100% reflecting diffuse white surface.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The *noise-based speed* is defined as the exposure that will lead to a given signal-to-noise ratio on individual pixels.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Two ratios are used, the 40:1 ("excellent image quality") and the 10:1 ("acceptable image quality") ratio.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] These ratios have been subjectively determined based on a resolution of 70 pixels per cm (178 DPI) when viewed at 25 cm (9.8 inch) distance.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The noise is defined as the standard deviation of a weighted average of the luminance and color of individual pixels.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The noise-based speed is mostly determined by the properties of the sensor and somewhat affected by the noise in the electronic gain and AD converter.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In addition to the above speed ratings, the standard also defines the *standard output sensitivity* (SOS), how the exposure is related to the digital pixel values in the output image.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] where $H_{\mathrm {sos} }$ is the exposure that will lead to values of 118 in 8-bit pixels, which is 18 percent of the saturation value in images encoded as sRGB or with gamma = 2.2.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The standard specifies how speed ratings should be reported by the camera.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] If the noise-based speed (40:1) is *higher* than the saturation-based speed, the noise-based speed should be reported, rounded *downwards* to a standard value (e.g.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The rationale is that exposure according to the lower saturation-based speed would not result in a visibly better image.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In addition, an exposure latitude can be specified, ranging from the saturation-based speed to the 10:1 noise-based speed.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] If the noise-based speed (40:1) is *lower* than the saturation-based speed, or undefined because of high noise, the saturation-based speed is specified, rounded upwards to a standard value, because using the noise-based speed would lead to overexposed images.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The camera may also report the SOS-based speed (explicitly as being an SOS speed), rounded to the nearest standard speed rating.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] The SOS rating could be user controlled.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] In all cases, the camera should indicate for the white balance setting for which the speed rating applies, such as daylight or tungsten (incandescent light).
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Despite these detailed standard definitions, cameras typically do not clearly indicate whether the user "ISO" setting refers to the noise-based speed, saturation-based speed, or the specified output sensitivity, or even some made-up number for marketing purposes.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Because the 1998 version of ISO 12232 did not permit measurement of camera output that had lossy compression, it was not possible to correctly apply any of those measurements to cameras that did not produce sRGB files in an uncompressed format such as TIFF.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] Following the publication of CIPA DC-004 in 2006, Japanese manufacturers of digital still cameras are required to specify whether a sensitivity rating is REI or SOS.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] A greater SOS setting for a given sensor comes with some loss of image quality, just like with analog film.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] However, this loss is visible as image noise rather than grain.
[src:film-speed/film-speed] APS- and 35 mm-sized digital image sensors, both CMOS and CCD based, do not produce significant noise until about *ISO 1600*.
